<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="81" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="24" pageNumber="81">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="24" pageNumber="81">
This new species is similar to other members of 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Poa subsp. sect." order="Poales" pageId="24" pageNumber="81" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="section" section="Homalopoa" species="urubambensis" subSpecies="sect.">Poa sect. Homalopoa</taxonomicName>
s.l. from Peru, Bolivia and Argentina, all of which have open panicles and spikelets with 2-5(-8) florets, the lowermost florets hermaphroditic while the upper florets are pistillate. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="S. P. Sylvester &amp; Soreng" authorityYear="2016" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Poa urubambensis" order="Poales" pageId="24" pageNumber="81" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="urubambensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="81">Poa urubambensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is easily recognised in the field by the combination of an open-panicled inflorescence, glabrous lemmas and calluses, and exceptionally small anthers for members of 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Poa subsp. supersect." order="Poales" pageId="24" pageNumber="81" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="superSection" species="urubambensis" subSpecies="supersect." superSection="Homalopoa">Poa supersect. Homalopoa</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="S. P. Sylvester &amp; Soreng" authorityYear="2016" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Poa urubambensis" order="Poales" pageId="24" pageNumber="81" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="urubambensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="81">Poa urubambensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also bears resemblance to 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Poa oscariana" order="Poales" pageId="24" pageNumber="81" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="oscariana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="81">Poa oscariana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but is distinguished by a less robust habit, the leaf blades being mainly basal and the anthers being smaller.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="24" pageNumber="81">
This species was found during a large scale ecological study attempting to reconstruct the potential natural vegetation (PNV) and soils of the high-elevation Puna grasslands (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Heitkamp, F" journalOrPublisher="Progress in Physical Geography" pageId="27" pageNumber="84" pagination="576 - 601" publicationUrl="10.1177/0309133314544918" refId="B12" refString="Heitkamp, F, Sylvester, SP, Kessler, M, Sylvester, MDPV, Jungkunst, HF, 2014. Inaccessible Andean sites reveal human induced weathering in grazed soils. Progress in Physical Geography 38 (5): 576 - 601, DOI: 10.1177/0309133314544918" title="Inaccessible Andean sites reveal human induced weathering in grazed soils." url="10.1177/0309133314544918" volume="38" year="2014">Heitkamp et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Sylvester, SP" journalOrPublisher="Phytotaxa" pageId="29" pageNumber="86" publicationUrl="10.1111/jvs.12176" refId="B41" refString="Sylvester, SP, Sylvester, MDPV, Kessler, M, 2014. Inaccessible ledges as refuges for the natural vegetation of the high Andes. In: Journal of Vegetation Science., DOI: 10.1111/jvs.12176" title="Inaccessible ledges as refuges for the natural vegetation of the high Andes." url="10.1111/jvs.12176" volumeTitle="Journal of Vegetation Science." year="2014">Sylvester et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
for pilot studies). In this research, pristine zonal vegetation, only accessible with mountaineering equipment, was compared with surrounding slopes which have been grazed and burnt consistently over millennia (
<bibRefCitation author="Thompson, LG" journalOrPublisher="Nature" pageId="29" pageNumber="86" pagination="763 - 765" publicationUrl="10.1038/336763a0" refId="B43" refString="Thompson, LG, Davis, ME, Mosley-Thompson, E, Liu, K-b, 1988. Pre-Incan agricultural activity recorded in dust layers in two tropical ice cores. Nature 336 (6201): 763 - 765, DOI: 10.1038/336763a0" title="Pre-Incan agricultural activity recorded in dust layers in two tropical ice cores." url="10.1038/336763a0" volume="336" year="1988">Thompson et al. 1988</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Chepstow-Lusty, AJ" journalOrPublisher="Antiquity" pageId="26" pageNumber="83" pagination="824 - 833" publicationUrl="10.1017/S0003598X0008409X" refId="B3" refString="Chepstow-Lusty, AJ, Bennett, KD, Switsur, VR, Kendall, A, 1996. 4000 years of human impact and vegetation change in the central Peruvian Andes - with events paralleling the Maya record? Antiquity 70: 824 - 833, DOI: 10.1017/S0003598X0008409X" title="4000 years of human impact and vegetation change in the central Peruvian Andes - with events paralleling the Maya record?" url="10.1017/S0003598X0008409X" volume="70" year="1996">Chepstow-Lusty et al. 1996</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Chepstow-Lusty, AJ" journalOrPublisher="Climate of the Past" pageId="27" pageNumber="84" pagination="375 - 388" publicationUrl="10.5194/cp-5-375-2009" refId="B4" refString="Chepstow-Lusty, AJ, Frogley, MR, Bauer, BS, Leng, MJ, Boessenkool, KP, Carcaillet, C, Ali, AA, Gioda, A, 2009. Putting the rise of the Inca Empire within a climatic and land management context. Climate of the Past 5: 375 - 388, DOI: 10.5194/cp-5-375-2009" title="Putting the rise of the Inca Empire within a climatic and land management context." url="10.5194/cp-5-375-2009" volume="5" year="2009">2009</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Kuentz, A" journalOrPublisher="Holocene" pageId="27" pageNumber="84" pagination="1215 - 1226" publicationUrl="10.1177/0959683611409772" refId="B15" refString="Kuentz, A, Ledru, M, Thouret, J, 2011. Environmental changes in the highlands of the western Andean Cordillera, southern Peru, during the Holocene. Holocene 22 (11): 1215 - 1226, DOI: 10.1177/0959683611409772" title="Environmental changes in the highlands of the western Andean Cordillera, southern Peru, during the Holocene." url="10.1177/0959683611409772" volume="22" year="2011">Kuentz et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="S. P. Sylvester &amp; Soreng" authorityYear="2016" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Poa urubambensis" order="Poales" pageId="24" pageNumber="81" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="urubambensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="81">Poa urubambensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was a common element in undisturbed Puna vegetation in the Cordillera Urubamba, being found associated with 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Polylepis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Polylepis" order="Rosales" pageId="24" pageNumber="81" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="81">Polylepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Ruiz &amp; Pav. forests from three different sites and also found growing alongside other species new to science, e.g. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sylvester" authorityYear="2014" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Orobanchaceae" genus="Bartsia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Bartsia lydiae" order="Tubiflorae" pageId="24" pageNumber="81" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="lydiae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="81">Bartsia lydiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
S.P. 
<bibRefCitation author="Sylvester, SP" journalOrPublisher="Phytotaxa" pageId="29" pageNumber="86" pagination="041 - 046" refId="B40" refString="Sylvester, SP, 2014. Bartsia lydiae, a new species of Bartsia sect. Laxae (Orobanchaceae) from the southern Peruvian Andes with a revised key to Bartsia sect. Laxae. Phytotaxa 164 (1): 041 - 046" title="Bartsia lydiae, a new species of Bartsia sect. Laxae (Orobanchaceae) from the southern Peruvian Andes with a revised key to Bartsia sect. Laxae" volume="164" year="2014">Sylvester (2014</bibRefCitation>
: 41). Following indicator species analyses, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="S. P. Sylvester &amp; Soreng" authorityYear="2016" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Poa urubambensis" order="Poales" pageId="24" pageNumber="81" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="urubambensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="81">Poa urubambensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been found as an indicator species for the PNV, due to its frequency and abundance within relict patches of near natural vegetation (Sylvester et al., 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="81">unpubl. data</emphasis>
). This species has not been found in accessible, disturbed or secondary, vegetation at similar or lower elevations in the Andes of the Cuzco region, despite a more thorough botanical exploration. This may relate to its susceptibility to disturbance from grazing and burning (Sylvester, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="81">pers. observation</emphasis>
).
</paragraph>
